{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"alias":"snide-cut-mussel","description":"## Summary\nTicket write operations fail hard on git `index.lock` contention and NEVER self-heal:\na single interrupted/crashed commit leaves a stale\n`.git/worktrees/<tracker>/index.lock` that wedges **every** subsequent ticket write\n(`comment`, `edit`, `create`, `link`, `tag`, …) until a human manually removes it. Even\n*transient* contention (two clones committing at once) surfaces as a hard error with no\nretry. Locks should be transient and ticket operations should retry + reclaim provably-stale\nlocks to be self-healing.\n\n## Reproduction Steps\n1. Drive any ticket write through `rebar._store.event_append.stage_and_commit` (e.g.\n   `rebar comment <id> \"...\"`).\n2. Simulate an interrupted commit by leaving a stale git index lock:\n   `touch \"$(git -C <tracker> rev-parse --git-dir)/index.lock\"` (no git process holds it).\n3. Run `rebar comment <id> \"anything\"` again.\n\nObserved in the wild: after an interrupted `rebar comment`, a ~15-minute-old\n`/Users/.../.git/worktrees/-tickets-tracker/index.lock` (0 bytes, no owning process per\n`lsof`) blocked five consecutive `rebar comment` retries; the store only recovered after a\nmanual `rm` of the lock file.\n\n## Expected vs Actual\n- **Expected:** a transient `index.lock` contention is retried with bounded backoff and\n  succeeds once the peer releases; a *provably stale* `index.lock` (no live owning git\n  process / older than a threshold) is detected and reclaimed automatically — mirroring the\n  stale-lock reclamation rebar ALREADY does for its own mkdir write-lock\n  (`_store/lock.py::_mkdir_lock_is_stale` / `_reclaim_mkdir_lock`). Ticket writes are\n  self-healing in the common case; only a genuinely-held lock (live peer) waits/fails.\n- **Actual:** `stage_and_commit` (`src/rebar/_store/event_append.py:145-175`) shells out to\n  `git add`/`git commit` and raises `StoreError(\"Error: git commit failed while holding\n  lock: … Unable to create '<gitdir>/index.lock': File exists. Another git process seems to\n  be running …\")` on the FIRST failure — no retry, no backoff, no stale detection. The\n  rebar `_store/lock.py` write lock is held around this, but that lock only reclaims its OWN\n  mkdir lock; the git-owned `index.lock` created transiently by `git add`/`git commit` is\n  not covered by any retry or staleness check, so one dead commit wedges all writes.\n\n## Context / root cause\nTwo lock layers exist and only one self-heals:\n- `_store/lock.py` (rebar write lock: fcntl + mkdir) — ALREADY reclaims a provably-stale\n  mkdir lock (owner stamp `<host>:<pid>`, dead-pid probe).\n- git's `index.lock` (created per `git add`/`git commit` inside `stage_and_commit`) — NOT\n  covered. Interrupted/killed commits (CI cancellation, `^C`, OOM, a crashed peer) strand it.\n\nThe `edf7`/`6818` history in the surrounding comments shows related git-race hardening\n(surfacing stderr, healing UU/unmerged paths), but transient/stale `index.lock` itself is\nstill fatal-on-first-try.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `stage_and_commit` (and the sibling inline committers `txn.py::claim_core`/\n      `transition_core`, `compact.py`) retry a git `index.lock` \"File exists / Another git\n      process seems to be running\" failure with bounded exponential backoff (small, capped\n      total wait) before surfacing an error\n- [ ] A *provably stale* `index.lock` (no live owning git process AND/OR older than a\n      configurable threshold) is detected and reclaimed automatically, reusing/mirroring the\n      staleness logic in `_store/lock.py` (`_mkdir_lock_is_stale` / `_reclaim_mkdir_lock`);\n      a genuinely-held lock (live peer within the window) is NOT stolen\n- [ ] A concurrency test: two processes committing to the same tracker serialize and BOTH\n      succeed (no spurious hard failure from transient `index.lock` contention)\n- [ ] A stale-lock test: a pre-created `index.lock` with no owning process is reclaimed and\n      the ticket write succeeds without manual intervention\n- [ ] The retry/reclaim is fail-safe: a lock genuinely held by a live peer still waits within\n      budget then surfaces a clear, actionable error (never silently drops the write, never\n      corrupts the index)\n- [ ] No regression to the existing `edf7` stderr-surfacing and `6818` unmerged-path healing\n      behavior","id":"562f-fed4-231d-4dac","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"bug","title":"Ticket writes fail hard on git index.lock — add retry + stale-lock reclamation (self-healing)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1783632744918783001,"uuid":"d8b4cfda-b4a6-49a0-b84a-0e2e1cf19b39"}